result.execSummary:
The defendant Cody T. Witt was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of THC [Modifiers: as a Party to a Crime], an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(e).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

cases #13CF493 and #14CF81 called at 10:31am.
Defendant Cody T. Witt in court with Attorney Nathan Otis.  ADA Monica Hall appears for the State of Wisconsin.  

Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights given; plea of " Guilty " entered on Count #1; factual basis stipulated; the Court accepts the plea, finds Mr. Witt guilty of Count #1, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses Counts # 2 & #3.

On Count # 1, the Court withholds sentence, and places Mr. Witt on Probation for two year, with conditions:
--to undergo AODA assessment and follow through with treatment recommendations
--to undergo any other assessment, treatment, and counseling as deemed appropriate by the Agent
--no possession or consumption of alcohol unless otherwise authorized by the Agnet
--no possession or consumption of controlled substances without a valid prescription
--to take all prescribed medications only as prescribed
--no contact with any known drug offenders except for treatment purposes, and except for incidental contact for work or school purposes, or as otherwise excepted by the Agent 
--to submit to random urinalyses or other drug testing
--to obtain/maintain fulltime employment and/or education program as approved by the Agent
--to pay costs of $243 plus $200 DNA surcharge 
--to pay $90 in drug testing-related fees, joint and several with the co-defendant Timothea Stinnett

The Court indicates that if the DNA surcharge is found to be unconstitutional, and the Defendant has not yet paid the surcharge, then the Judgment of Conviction is to be amended to remove the surcharge payment requirement.  If the DNA surcharge has been paid and the ruling that found the DNA surcharge unconstitutional directs the clerks to reimburse the amount paid, then the clerk is to refund the amount paid to the Defendant. If the reimbursement is not mandated, then the amount will be kept.

Days credit for time already served:  1 day
recess 11:06am.
Plea/sentencing hearing on May 6, 2014 at 10:30 am.
